VHindustani classical on a keyboard
p3
sVnews
p4
VNoted keyboard player V. Sitaramiah, showed that the instrument can become the main thing, if the artiste is really adept. A little later, he proved his prowess with the harmonium at the Thyagaraya Gana Sabha last week.  In both, his grip on the idiom of Hindustani music was laudable. His prowess was on display when he played Hindustani melodiesPoorviandSohinion the keyboard. TheBandishhe played in this melody set toMadhya LayaandDhrut LayainTeen Taalwas engaging. The many musical graces were brought about in this phase. Vocalist Mahua Mukherjee of Kolkata then presented aKhyalinRaag Behagwith aVilambitcomposition inEk Taaland another inJhap Taal,Madhya Layaand inTeen Taal, Dhrut Laya, making a great impact on audience. Seetharamiah accompanied her on harmonium with good anticipation.Then, there was the rhythmic solo performance by tabla maestro, Javed Najmuddin, who filled the packed house with plenty of rhythmic sounds of differentgharanaslike that ofAjaradaandLukhnovi. He also gave a vocal display of rhythmic structures asbols. HisRelaandKayadaexercises were well received, for their thrilling rhythm variations. Anant Nyalkalkar was on harmonium and Syed-u-Rehman providedLeheraon sarangi. Later, the Sabha felicitated Najmuddin and presented him with the title of `Tabla-Ratna'. After the meeting, young Sushanto Nandi, renderedRaag Jogon flute, set toMadhya LayaandDhrut Laya Teen Taal. Then Mahua Mukherjee rendered a mellifluousThumri, Kakarun Sajnipopularised by the late Bade Ghulam Ali Khan. This was followed by the rendition of adadraand a MeeraBhajan,Savan Ke Rang Rachee. Then Sitharamiah gave a solo on his keyboard presenting the ragaMalkauns. The compositions in this raga were inMadhya Laya- JhaptalandDhrut Laya-Teen Taal. Javed Najmuddin accompanied him on the tabla.G.S.Bottom Template Starts
